# Imperatives — Memory Drill

## Purpose

Drill perfective imperative forms of high-frequency verbs. Most are irregular — the form cannot be predicted from the present or aorist stem. Must be memorised as frozen forms.

Prompt format: English command → Greek imperative (sg)
Example: "Come!" → "Έλα!"

## Why this belongs in memory drills

Regular imperative formation (-ε or -σε ending) is learnable as a rule. These forms are not regular. Each must be memorised individually. They appear constantly in real speech and cannot be avoided.

## Phase 3 core set

| English     | Imperative sg | Present     | Notes |
|-------------|---------------|-------------|-------|
| Come!       | Έλα!          | έρχομαι     | Suppletive — completely different stem |
| Say! / Tell!| Πες!          | λέω         | Irregular |
| Give!       | Δώσε!         | δίνω        | Semi-irregular |
| Bring!      | Φέρε!         | φέρνω       | Irregular |
| Do! / Make! | Κάνε!         | κάνω        | Regular pattern but high-frequency anchor |
| Go!         | Πήγαινε!      | πηγαίνω     | Imperfective form used; πήγαινε not πήγε |
| Take!       | Πάρε!         | παίρνω      | Irregular |
| See! / Look!| Κοίτα!        | κοιτάζω     | Truncated form used in speech |
| Eat!        | Φάε!          | τρώω        | Suppletive |
| Drink!      | Πιες!         | πίνω        | Suppletive |
| Write!      | Γράψε!        | γράφω       | Regular -ψε |
| Read!       | Διάβασε!      | διαβάζω     | Regular -σε |
| Listen!     | Άκουσε!       | ακούω       | Regular -σε |
| Look!       | Κοίτα! / Κοίταξε! | κοιτάζω | Two acceptable forms |
| Wait!       | Περίμενε!     | περιμένω    | Regular |

## Plural imperatives (secondary)

Greek adds -τε for plural/formal imperatives. Drill singular first; introduce plural forms once singular is automatic. The pattern is mostly predictable once you know the singular.

## Drill modes

**Forward**: English command → Greek imperative (singular)
  - "Come! →?" → "Έλα!"

**Reverse**: Greek imperative → English
  - "Πες! →?" → "Say! / Tell!"

## Grouping suggestion

- Phase A: Έλα, Πες, Δώσε, Φέρε, Κάνε (5 most frequent)
- Phase B: All 15

## Time limits

Forward: 4 seconds
Reverse: 3 seconds

## Notes

- Present these as vocabulary items, not grammar transformations — do not show the paradigm table, just the command form
- Negative imperative (Μην + subjunctive) is separate and should not be mixed into this drill
- Plural/formal forms (-τε) are predictable once singular known — note this but don't drill separately until Phase 3 is solid
